<h2 id="factstorming">Routine in depth — Factstorming</h2>

<p>Some routines need more than a table row. This one runs at the seams of units — the start, and right before a defense.</p>

<p>Groups of three or four, one recorder, one question with many right answers, four minutes. Pour out every FACT you can — things you know, not ideas you're inventing. The rules: everything goes on the list; nobody judges during the storm; build on what you hear; stop when time stops. Judging quality comes AFTER — and in this class, "after" means the harvest board becomes source-evaluation material: which of these facts would survive a check?</p>

<p>The variant you'll meet in Unit 2: after the room storms, we ask the class AI platform the same question and put its list next to ours. Three things always happen. The AI lists facts nobody in the room knew — and at least one needs verifying before we trust it. The room lists facts the AI didn't have — and they're almost always local: the specific lake, the street that floods, what your grandmother remembers. And someone asks whether we needed the AI at all, which is exactly the right question to leave the room holding.</p>

<p>(Factstorming has a sibling — Brainstorming, for generating new ideas rather than retrieving known facts. It arrives when this course starts designing things, in Units 3 and 6.)</p>

<p>Rubric language for all of it lives at <a href="/foundations/the-rubric/">The Rubric Explained</a>.</p>

